WoW what a journey!

My husband, Jonathan has never been one to seek out the spotlight. His work demands no ego. He has left all of “our” story for me to tell, so I’ll continue to tell it… right now.

My husband is a PhD/Economist from the University of Chicago. He’s a lover of books and mathematics. When his children are learning physics, he goes out and buys the textbook, just to refresh his mind. He is always learning. Always.

He is a Renaissance Man as well.

That same man took a break from his job as said economist, to, um.. join the #AirForce and become a pilot, because he wanted to serve our country.

In his 50s, he climbed Mt. Kili … just because it was there.

And now, in 4 months time, he went from “dad bod” to competitive #bodybuilder.

💥Was he #1 in his officer training class? No
💥Was he the first in his group to get to the top of Mt Kili? No.
💥Did he graduate #1 at his University? No.
💥Did he take home first place in this bodybuilding show? No.

💥💥Did any of the above change the way he is because of a first or last place? Absolutely NOT.💥💥

There is a lesson here for all of us. You do the work you do because you love the challenge, the growth, the love of sport. Whatever it is. 

If you do it to try and gain respect and validation for yourself from outside sources, you will constantly be hustling for the next high of external adoration, rather than doing it for internal one. That’s more exhausting than this bodybuilding prep.

Who knew at age 60 you could START something like this. 

It is not too late to start anything. And you don’t need to be categorized as one thing your entire life. My husband is evidence of this. Because he doesn’t honestly care what others think of him. 

We can all learn something about ourselves if we do what we feel in our hearts is the right thing for us. 
I learn from him every day.
(Except I am not reading high school books again- once was enough).

Thank you @solid_fitnessinc and @motiv8nu2 for keeping my husband on point. And ty @npc_illinois and @npc_mid_american_winterclassic for the love and support.

👏I am so freakin proud of my husband. 

💥Yes it takes food discipline. 
💥Yes it takes a certain mindset. 
💥Yes it isn’t easy. 

Buuuuut- in FOUR MONTHS - he went from “dad-60year old bod” to THIS!

👙I knew my transformation was miraculous. Who knew my body, after so much #trauma, could turn into a bikini competitor who could actually compete.

👅And his transformation is also inspirational. I mean- after 15 years of marriage - Thank you @pattistanger again for introducing us- I am still drooling. 

💕He did this for him, but he also did this for US.

🥅He did not place in the show, but that was never the goal. The goal was to be better than he was last year. And holy sh!t did he do that & more.

💍Marriage, relationships, intimacy- all of it can get stagnant if we are focus on complaining about ourselves and our partners. I complained a whole heck of a lot about my “womanhood” being stripped from me after my emergency #hysterectomy & #ptsd. But when I decided to do something about it- I regained strength and love for myself and was able to share a new whole part of me with my spouse. Someone he lost for a couple of years while I mourned my previous life.

💪And like me, Jonathan wanted to show up as my strong protector. My alpha male. My gorgeous, sexy #soulmate. He wanted to change it up for not just him, but for me… for US.

😘We both said to each other: “You FEEL incredible.” That is not the touch of one’s body. That is something we FEEL in our souls.

😍I am so proud of this Univ of Chicago nerd. And I am so proud of anyone who grabs a second, third, fourth chance where they can.

💡Those small wins help propel you forward. With hard work and discipline, you too can leave the past where it belongs and look forward to a stronger, more confident future. 

#Thisis60

The weekend was the most magical, spiritual, love-filled, warm, chic, kind, beautiful, heartwarming one I have ever felt.

I knew it would be incredible, but how much so, was a big question.

When a girl or boy comes of age (12/13) for their b’neimitzvot, they give a #DvarTorah (their own words in relation to their Torah portion). 

That Torah portion is determined by the date you select. So think of the #fivebooksofmoses and all the stories in the #Bible. Then think, “this is the date around my child’s 12th birthday, so we will choose this.” 

Our daughter’s birthday fell on the exact day of the #BatMitzvah. Pre-destined, if you will.

Her Torah portion is called #Vayishlach and it is about Rachel & Her giving birth to her second child.

And how she died during childbirth.

RIGHT. 

Let that sit with you for a moment.

Our daughter did not want to discuss this topic AT ALL! So much so, she asked to change her mitzvah date.

It wasn’t moving. She knew and said in her speech “Since I am seen as an adult to G-d, in order to grow, I need to let go of the past to move forward with what does not serve me in my future.”

So she spoke of the pain. She spoke of her anger, her loneliness. She spoke of the fact that this Torah portion was always meant for her. That the story of her own mother’s death and survival is part of her story, but not the focal point of her story for the rest of her life.

She spoke eloquently. She was poised and captured a feeling many of us in the room were feeling. Pride & Power.

She regained strength. She was vulnerable. She was brave. And she “grew up.”

What a thing to witness and feel right before our eyes.

A job so well-done, she gave her speech again in the evening.

After #havdalah, where we end the sabbath and welcome the new week. Our #rabbi @mendybenhiyoun sang like an angel with the #klezmerfoundation accompanying him, the children sang from their hearts and souls and you felt the vibration elevate 100-fold.

We all felt it.

She did a phenomenal job. And then it was time to party. Hard.

"According to the CDC, over 80% of maternal deaths in the United States are preventable. To prevent these tragic deaths, which are occurring at increasing rates, we must first know why they’re happening.

This year’s Maternal Health Awareness Day theme is Know Why". *ACOG

This woman right here next to me is also a survivor of one of the most devastating conditions known in maternal health as Amniotic Fluid Embolism. 

We both are survivors, warriors and thrivers. 

Learning, growing and helping others with their traumas from our own experiences.  We have leaned on each other through some of the most difficult of times and continue to this day.

Just because you get through the "worst" of your experience, does not mean you are "through" it.  Post-trauma, #grief, loss of self and what you thought your "birthing moment" would bring, connection or disconnection to your spouse and so on, and so on.

It sucks.
Trauma sucks.
There are ALWAYS people who survived "better" than others and survivors who have guilt, we when others did not.

We have both had our share of WHYs in this recovery process.

I have my destination and so does Miranda.

Miranda Klassen has (since her own AFE) dedicated her entire being to her family and the pursuit of ending this horrific condition which affects 1 in 40,000 families.

With her tirelessly working to develop safety protocols to educate clinicians and helping families through the biggest health and psychological challenges when in the throes of an AFE, The AFE FOUNDATION will eventually KNOW WHY this happens so we can prevent it from happening in our lifetime.

You may never know the WHY this happened to you, but you can glean some hope from others that you don't have to be stuck forever in the state of trauma. If you can find others who've been there and can support you through the "worst" of times. it will get better. For me, it was finding Miranda. 

I hope you can find your "Miranda" out there.

Namaste-

Stephanie knew she was going to die.
She spent months preparing herself, her doctors and her loved ones.

No one believed her.
Then, moments after giving birth to her son, Stephanie died.
It happened exactly how she knew it would. What she didn’t know was that death would become an experience that shaped the rest of her life.

In her international bestseller, 37 Seconds: Dying Revealed Heaven’s Help, Stephanie shares her quest to discover what really happened while she was dead.

Listening to Stephanie narrate her audiobook is like reliving her incredible journey right along with her.
 
Before Stephanie Arnold died, she had been an Emmy-nominated, award-winning TV producer who spent nearly three decades creating and producing TV shows, music videos and documentaries. Then she met the love of her life, and Stephanie decided the only thing she wanted to produce was a family.

Little did she know this fateful decision would—quite literally—lead her to the end of one life and the beginning of another.

Stephanie is now an award-winning, international best-selling author and inspirational speaker on a mission to help others realize that connecting with our intuition
can not only enhance our lives, but can very well save them.

I live by this M.O.

I’ve read a lot about missed opportunities when one senses something, yet says nothing. 

Sometimes the results are not so tragic and other times, lives were lost.

How many of us “wish” we had said something when our intuition told us there’s something off? 

I’ve been wrong many times to bury my head in the sand because I don’t want “negative energy” following me. I have thought “this isn’t any of my business, so I’ll shut up.”

Here’s the rub- THAT IS EXACTLY what people did to me when I was begging for help to save my life.  It is what millions of people did in Eastern Europe during the Holocaust. And what thousands of women did to stand up against being victimized.

We can stand in silence, squeaky clean and love from afar or we can love up close and personal, getting shit all over ourselves. 

I have been on the receiving end of sexual harassment, bullying, misogynistic comments, improper touching, abandonment, vicious mean girls, physical abuse, thievery, and so much more.

When each event had run its course I was “ok.” Bruised and battered, but I survived. I was confident I took the brunt of what was given and it didn’t kill me.

I kept my head down and I moved on. Praying none of what happened to me would ever happen to anyone else. I was in denial. I moved on.

I was wrong to not help others who were weaker. Hell, I was weaker. 

Then I died. And my perspective changed.

I am an #advocate. I’m a #healer. I’m #strongAF. And I do my best to help support others with my newfound voice.

I’m not afraid of the shit any longer.  When the thing you are most afraid of happens (like losing your life), you can handle anything. 

Bring on the heavy shit. I’m down.

💡How many of you FEEL your way through your decisions?

I have been guilty of second guessing my #intuition even after my #neardeathexperience. WHY?

Because it doesn’t seem logical that an instinct, something you can’t hold or see, can have any weight in the decisions you make.

Feelings are part of your senses. Just like sight, sound or touch. 

The next time the hair on the back of your neck stands up, or a choice gives you pause, process the feelings and then think to yourself: “What happens if I choose my gut?”

For me, every friggin time I went against my gut I was wrong.

My protector. My hero. My everything. I love you.❤️😘💕

For those of you wondering if you can find love again after your spouse passes and you have 63 years of marriage under your belt, the answer (from my mother’s perspective) is YES.

Is it the same? 
No

But thank goodness - because if it were, you’d always be comparing what you had to what you have. 

You grow. You learn. You love. You experience tremendous loss.

And then, when you are in your next chapter, a second life if you will AND an octogenarian, you learn what you won’t settle for or need.  In essence, you don’t ”get what you want, you get what you need!”

I know in my heart that’s not what the Rolling Stones meant when they wrote that line.  But how I translate it is: she may want to have some form of what she had with my dad, but she has what she needs. And that really is amazing. 

She is enjoying her second life. She is living it up. She has someone by her side who adores and bears witness to her life’s existence (especially when her children, grandchildren and great grandchildren are not around).

She’s been my Father’s Valentine since she was 15 & he was 16. It’s time for her to be someone else’s.

Happy Valentine’s Day everyone. 

I hope this inspires someone on this love-filled day.

I’m 51. Biologically. 237 Spiritually. I’ve been #bodybuilding now for 3 years erasing the signs of #ptsd and aging on my body which had been ravaged by my #birthtrauma and #amnioticfluidembolism. 

I know eventually I will need a #blepheroplasty to lift the eyelids in order to see, but could there be something out there to help stave off the procedure well into the distant future? After all of my mandatory surgeries and recoveries, the idea of any operation scared the crap out of me. 

Many lasers, #chemicalpeels and supplements do work, but sometimes, you hear of a “new thing” that might work to reduce the signs of “maturity” and help “lift” where others fail to do so. I did my research and read so many reviews. No pain, no gain, I know the saying, but I have a serious aversion to pain. So I waited until I found something which suited me. 

And here it is @sofwavemed.
* Sofwave uses high-frequency ultrasonic pulses which raise the temperature at the dermis layer. The healing process generates the growth of elastin & collagen fibers causing the skin to “lift”.

-FDA- cleared.
-Award-Winning Technology:
Elle Magazine Future of Beauty Award Winner 2021
Cosmopolitan Magazine 2022 Holy Grail Beauty Award
NewBeauty Magazine 2022 Beauty Awards 
SHAPE Magazine 2022 Skin
-Safe, fast & effective to lift eyebrows, skin under chin, neck tissue, and so much more.

Is this vain? Probably. 
Will this make me feel better about my droopy face & stop pulling at my neck? Yes.
Am I willing to try this? Absolutely.

I asked my sister in #Boca who she’d recommend & she said @allenbyderm so I booked an appt to learn more.

But is it worth it? 
You tell me. Here is the “before” & “after”  ONE HOUR apart.

My experience:

4. I left the spa and went straight to dinner with no one wondering if I did anything to my face the previous hour.

I have gotten rejected a lot in my life.

A job. A friendship. A relationship. 

I “thought” I wanted them because they made sense at the time. But the reality is, they were a distraction to dealing with the core of my pain. 

Who the heck wants to deal with that when we can "keep it moving" because as we move farther and farther away from our pain point it shouldn’t bother us anymore- right?!

The issue with this maladaptive response to pain is that when things fell through, (which they do over and over again), I, personally, have felt empty & worthless. Of zero value to anyone, including myself.

It took years to learn how to protect myself, and now it has taken years to unlearn it. 

I’ve learned, even through writing a successful book, getting the media attention, finding the love of my life and getting my body back- I was a genius at compartmentalizing the deepest part of my pain. 

And when I’d get rejected that pain reared its’ ugly head. 

I didn’t want to see it. 
I definitely didn’t want to deal with it. 
I didn’t feel the need to do any more freaking healing work. 

So I would stay "busy", and that worked until it didn't anymore.

Once I started dealing with the moment of flatline (physically), dealt with childhood issues, held a space for my inner child, & discussed how I could stop any ancestral trauma by openly discussing my fears & control with my children, the floodgates of ACCEPTANCE started to rush in.

Divine Timing of Rejection. Trust the Universe. And DETACH from outcome.

Rejection is the gift to give way to your ultimate reward.

If it makes you uncomfortable, you need to ask why? 

Why is that person affecting me so much?

Why is not being accepted into that circle causing me so much discomfort?

Why do I NEED whatever it is so much?

It’s not easy. I know. But it is possible. 

You deserve to make decisions about your life without the past affecting your future.

💡Ever want to run and hide away from feeling the pain?

Is avoidance better than confrontation?

❤️‍🩹Do you think with every passing day, the healing will happen, gradually?

In some cases- maybe.

I’ve been guilty of believing all those things. And I have also believed if I stay busy and focus on the positives, I can replace the pain with #love. 

The shame and guilt which accompany pain can only be released if you allow yourself to FEEL IT.

We are all so good at self-preservation. Controlling the narrative. Keeping it moving, because if we don’t we might collapse.

But here’s the rub- the cells of the body remember #trauma. I was in an #acupuncture session working on my #scars and all of a sudden 💥 I start bawling like I was four years old. I threw up. And when I got home, I slept for 12 hours straight.

I kept avoiding the moment of impact, really well, all those years. I got to be an expert in going a few layers deep, but avoiding the core.

Interesting that my core pain is literally in the core of my body.

I had to go back into the 🔥. I thought I had done a lot of healing work, and I have. You have. But if these raw emotions unexpectedly come out, then allowing yourself to feel it (not run away from it) will actually help you HEAL IT.

😩It is never going to be as painful as the first time you experienced your #trauma. But the anxiety not allowing you to get near the feeling will cripple you long term.

⁉️Ask yourself: what can you do to safely feel what you need to in order to heal what once destroyed you.

💥From this to THAT! 

🥲Scars are still there, but they fade.

😩Trauma is still there, but it fades.

💔Love for myself wasn’t there, it grew.

🦵Zero muscle and gravity took its toll but eventually a strong 💪 physique showed up, because I DID.

☄️We can all bounce back and forth from one extreme to another. We can feel crappy about ourselves and let trauma drag us down to look the way we feel. 

OR…

💡We can show up as best we can- moment by moment- and take the things that happened to us, (because you can’t change a f*cking thing about that) and kick yourself into gear. 

Realize 
✅YOU ARE A BADASS! 
✅YOU ARE A SURVIVOR. 
✅YOU ARE A WARRIOR. 

And does it suck you ever got kicked down in the first place- 💯. 
But did you die? Permanently? 

Then if you are waiting for a #sign - HERE IT IS ⬅️

Start TODAY. One little thing. Look in the mirror and say “I am proud of you. You survived what many do not. You are doing better today than yesterday.”

💩If you have a shitty day tomorrow, you are stronger tomorrow to deal with it because you are building off of the strength you had today. 

🥊When you get knocked down after the healing starts, the fall is a much shorter one because you’ve already been through Hell. 

➡️Imagine if you don’t deal with the pain EVER.. what happens?

🤮I’ll tell you, because I am guilty of compartmentalizing pain for years. Well- when you avoid it and you have a death in the family, or you get sick with a diff illness or someone close to you leaves you… you almost can’t handle anymore. You become more crippled with doom and gloom than if you dealt with the previous blow beforehand.

🙏Trust me that I wouldn’t be where I am today without going back into that damn 🔥! No other way out of it than through it.

🥂Here’s to the baddest biatches out there. Yes I’m talking to you.

Take this as your sign that I have your back and so do many others who love and respect you. 

Go! Go! Goooooooooo! 📣

I choose you. Today. Tomorrow. Always. (Even when I’m bitchy)!

10 years ago no one knew whether I would live or die.

10 years ago, I was defeated.

10 years ago, I still had a family and a husband who had hope and love and prayers I would come out of this and get back to “normal.”

I was never going to get back to normal. 

I’d never be the same.

And THAT IS A GREAT THING.

At the time, I wanted to come out of my #amnioticfluidembolism whole. But I’d been cut, torn apart, rebuilt and left without my uterus and my psyche. I’d been destroyed.

But here’s the thing about hitting rock bottom (and being clinically dead for #37Seconds and on Life support was it for me), you have nowhere to go- but UP!

You are never going to be the same post massive trauma, but through therapy & support, you can make the choice to be different, stronger, #antifragile and a #warrior. 

I made a choice just THREE YEARS AGO at 49 years old to do just that.

And the photo on the right is a result of that mindset. 

I’m here as a witness to your #trauma that anything is possible, you just need to take the first step, make the choice and do not stress when you falter. You’ve taken the first step in your mind. The rest will follow.

I love your soul. From mine to yours.

Today is AFE Awareness Day. 

As most of you know, 10 years ago, MAY, I had a very complex and life-threatening Amniotic Fluid Embolism when I gave birth to our last child Jacob.

It is a condition where amniotic cells get into the mother’s bloodstream and if you happen to be allergic to it, well, in many cases, you don’t survive.

It is unpreventable & unpredictable. 

Two unsuspecting pregnant women will experience an AFE EACH WEEK. One will not make it. And depending at what moment in the birthing process, neither will the baby.

The AFE (Amniotic Fluid Embolism) Foundation is the ONLY foundation dedicated to research,  raising awareness and education to our health care workers, supporting families in their desperate time of need and with the largest database of AFEs in the world, we will, in our lifetime, put an END to AFE. 

It’s amazing how a known condition of more than 100 years has only been more understood in the last 15 years because of our foundation.

We are a small grassroots org, where the ones affected are the ones who support it. 

The reality is: ANYONE could need us one day. AFE knows no race, color, religion, way of delivery, way of conception. It can affect ANY PREGNANCY.

Ways you can help:

As always, 100% of my book proceeds go to the AFE Foundation. #37Seconds 

Or on Audible. (Yes, I read the narrative). @dreamscape_media #37Seconds @audible

When tragedy hits, you have many ways to deal with it. 

First and foremost- you mourn. You mourn the loss of who you were before all of your life went to Hell. You sleep. You have #ptsd. You laugh less. You have zero appreciation for the frivolous things you used to love. Your family worries. You are supposed to be grateful you survived, but you can barely think about that because you will collapse knowing how close a call it was you would be a statistic in all the worst possible ways.

Both @thebirthtrauma_mama & I went through all of these emotions and many more after surviving our very own #amnioticfluidembolisms. We still have days of struggle but we don’t “sugar coat” it for “the gram.” In many ways - everything which has happened to us, happened for us because we both pivoted to help not just ourselves and our families, but many others who are steps behind us in the throes of their very own traumas. 

Kayleigh has created a huge platform with TikTok & social, using her experience as a licensed therapist to educate people about #birthtrauma. 

She also sits on the board of the @afefoundation with me, helping families during their desperate time of need.

This interview was a long time coming and we discussed all things #intuition , #afe #trauma & we even laughed a little.

It’s always good to connect with someone who has been there and understands your “road less taken.” 

I commended her level of compassion and empathy and said “wow- you are so understanding of my husband’s plight during all of this. You must’ve been amazing with your husband!” She answered: “Oh no- I was not that way with him.”

It’s good to know we are all human. 

You can listen to the podcast by clicking link in my story.

#nofilter

There are times in our lives where we look forward to celebrations and enjoying moments with loved ones.

There are times where one chapter ends and another begins, when you look forward to moving on.

We are only a couple of weeks out from graduation, end of school years for the other two children and completing our time here in Chicago.

This is a “happy” time. This photo is of a moment my friends came over to celebrate a little goodbye dinner/cocktail for us.

But in true #nofilter form, the facade looks happier than the inside.

I am having a hard time socializing. I am becoming more introverted and I had no idea why. Thank goodness my husband is picking up the slack and becoming this social butterfly while I keep moving inward.

I’m having a difficult time eating right and working out. I’m unmotivated to do anything except the bare-minimum to get through these next few weeks.

Yes, transitions are hard. Moving is hard. But when I looked at the date, I realized, I am a few days away from my “death” date.

And even though life looks great for many on the outside, on the inside trauma lives. No matter how long you’ve been “good”, there are moments, as happy as they should be, where you can feel really bad. 

This is a reminder for you and for me that it is ok to be uncomfortable. Because until I stopped and noticed I was feeling this way, I didn’t recognize what was actually happening.
I stopped being hard on myself and disappointed with the fact I wasn’t working at optimal speed and just became what I was/AM in this moment.

Life events will still happen. You might not be your best, but hopefully you have that someone you can lean on to help you during this time.  You only need to speak up about how you feel & say NO to things you cannot mentally attend if you cannot.

Intuition can get clouded when you feel the blahs, but if you have a good sense of what you were before feeling this way, and your intuition isn’t working, THAT is actually valuable information your system is on overload.

Take good care of your heart and soul, then you can take care of everyone else’s.

My daughter has always been an #empath. In fact, all of my children are.

When children shy away from an individual or don’t want to embrace someone, take that as a sign to allow them the space to FEEL what is right for their soul.

They have a natural #intuition about things that gets muted over years and years of our projection and beliefs onto them.

Take a listen to what feels right for you after years of experience. Now try to go back to those moments when you were a child who KNEW instinctively someone wasn’t telling the truth. Then ask yourself…

WHAT IS MY CHILD SEEING THAT I CANNOT OR DO NOT WANT TO SEE?

They don’t have years of experience, but they do get flutters in their stomach. They do get headaches which have no explanation. They do get irritated around some folks. And they do run off and hide in a corner if they do not feel like socializing. 

Talk through what they are sensing. Validate their fears by listening. And don’t force them to do something with someone with whom they are uncomfortable. 

Their hearts are pure, where many are not.

The only thing standing in the way of your #intuition, is YOU.

Intuitively I believed I could do anything I set my mind to, but along the way I doubted I could do any of it. (Including saving my life).

Intuition and belief in self do go hand in hand. Doubt yourself, then how can you believe your soul can tell you the truth?

Never in a million years would I believe after all the #trauma my body suffered, I could be this athletic. For the record, I was always chosen last in sports, had no coordination and almost never participated in school sports.

But when I started going down this #bodybuilding path, I knew I could do it. Then others got in my head regarding “do you know how strict the diet is?” “You don’t have any muscle.” “You need to lift heavy!” I started to doubt what I believed to be true.

You are on your own path. Anyone telling you this is impossible to do is speaking about how impossible it would be for THEM to do it.

YOU know best. Your soul doesn’t lie, but your head will!

Stay the course and conquer it beautifully!

"Hi Stephanie. Thank you for sharing your story. Hearing someone who had a similar experience gives me comfort. You see I worked as a firefighter and began having premonitions about fires. I would run around and tell everybody just to validate this stuff. Then for a month or two, I had really intense visions involving HIV...which caused me to go to my doctor convinced that I needed to be tested (I'm married with 3 wonderful kids). Thankfully my doc believed me, and I went to get tested, insisting my wife accompany me to the clinic (she's an attorney and was highly skeptical). And you can guess what happened next...yep positive test. Six weeks later, I was retested and learned 1st test was a false positive and I do not have the virus. So while everyone said to just forget about it, I couldn't. I began volunteering at an HIV clinic, and this past May completed a PhD in Mental Health Counseling at the University of Georgia. My dissertation was called "A Leap of Faith: HIV/AIDS and the Role of Spiritual Coping." Sometimes I need to be reminded to appreciate this gift of intuition. Seeing your story on YouTube tonight was just what I needed to hear- Thank you so much for your courage in sharing your story".

My son, who is 10, said something quite prolific the other day. He said “We will remember this war like the Holocaust.”

Both Jonathan and I shut it down by saying “You cannot compare ANYTHING to the Holocaust.”

We were wrong. 

🧿The last time this many #Jews perished in a single day was during the Holocaust.

🧿The last time Jews were hunted and rounded up to be executed, The Holocaust.

🧿 A crowd of hundreds, in Sydney Australia,  was heard chanting in a video, "Gas the Jews", in reference to the gas chambers in concentration camps where millions perished.

After the Holocaust many were heard saying “NEVER AGAIN,” and look where we are today.

I’m saddened to say I quieted my son by telling him what he was saying was HORRIBLE. 

ME, the empath, the intuitive, the one who says “Sense it, Stay it!” 

Not only am I appalled I tried to downplay the severity of his words, but I was guilty of doing the very opposite of what I always preach.

So here I am, SPEAKING UP, learning, and helping with the very little influence I have to share important lessons I have learned  from “Three Wise Monkeys.”

🙈SEE NO EVIL - does it not exist? It does if you open your 👀!

-Open your eyes. Even your third eye. Watch the videos, yes they will be emblazoned in your mind. But you need to see the evil to KNOW it exists.

🙉HEAR NO EVIL- Listen to those you trust to keep YOU safe. I tell my children when they share something they’ve seen on social: “I need three trusted sources before we converse about this.” Repeating something you may not be sure is true is nothing but gossip and perpetuating a false narrative.

🙊SPEAK NO EVIL
This does NOT mean BE SILENT in the wake of seeing something you cannot ignore.  Even if you don’t understand, silence is no longer an option. 

Many cannot believe pure evil and hatred like this exists.

There is no disbelief in my son’s eyes. And I’m sure he wasn’t fully aware of what he was saying when he said it. But maybe he was.

I am so sorry Jacob, my son. You were right and unfortunately I was wrong. The war in Israel has all the markings of being remembered like The Holocaust.
